  "prompt": "How do I install things on Linux?",
  "response": "In Linux, there are several ways to install software depending on the distribution you're using:\n\n1. For Ubuntu/Debian-based distributions (using apt):\n```\nsudo apt update\nsudo apt install package-name\n```\n\n2. For Red Hat/Fedora-based distributions (using dnf or yum):\n```\nsudo dnf install package-name\n# or\nsudo yum install package-name\n```\n\n3. For Arch Linux (using pacman):\n```\nsudo pacman -S package-name\n```\n\n4. Using .deb files (Debian/Ubuntu):\n```\nsudo dpkg -i package-name.deb\n```\n\n5. Using .rpm files (Fedora/Red Hat):\n```\nsudo rpm -i package-name.rpm\n```\n\n6. Compiling from source:\n```\n./configure\nmake\nsudo make install\n```\n\n7. Using Snap (works on many distributions):\n```\nsudo snap install package-name\n```\n\n8. Using Flatpak (cross-distribution):\n```\nflatpak install package-name\n```\n\nThe most common and recommended method is using the package manager specific to your Linux distribution (like apt, dnf, or pacman).",
